        "content": "<p>Is there a library lemma somewhere that proves 0 is not odd? It feels weird to have to write my own proposition for this, especially when it's so simple to do this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">zero_not_odd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hx</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Odd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">by_contra</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">rcases</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hx</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">with</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hy</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">linarith</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The main issue I'm running into is that I don't know if there's a good search tool that would let me find the names of lemmas like this?</p>",
        "id": 451898706,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophia C",
        "timestamp": 1721175672
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you can prove simple propositions like that by <code>decide</code>:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">zero_not_odd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"n\">Odd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">decide</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 451900039,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1721176300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How does that work? <code>decide</code> seems like magic.</p>",
        "id": 451902445,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophia C",
        "timestamp": 1721177531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Nat.instDecidablePredOdd#doc\">docs#Nat.instDecidablePredOdd</a>. A <code>DecidablePred</code> instance means that for a predicate <code>P : Nat -&gt; Prop</code>, if you're given a statement of <code>P n</code>, there is an algorithm to determine whether <code>P n</code> is true or false.</p>",
        "id": 451903617,
        "sender_full_name": "Yakov Pechersky",
        "timestamp": 1721178219
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In this case, that algorithm says \"well, Odd means the same as determining that <code>n % 2 = 1</code>. And we have a decidable algorithm of determining that two Nats are the same. So we can rely on that algorithm.\" And then it takes your <code>0</code>, plugs it into <code>0 % 2 = 1</code> which reduces to <code>0 = 1</code> which is false (because of how Nats are constructed), so the negation of it is true. BTW, through <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Not.decidable#doc\">docs#Not.decidable</a>.</p>",
        "id": 451903801,
        "sender_full_name": "Yakov Pechersky",
        "timestamp": 1721178361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wonder in what generality it's true - at least for Nat and Int; clearly not for <code>ZMod n</code> (n odd)</p>",
